      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the goblin confusion! Let's talk about your sourdough starter without the mythical creatures this time. A temperature of 70°F (21°C) is on the cooler side for a sourdough starter. The ideal range is usually between 75°F and 80°F (24°C to 27°C) for optimal yeast and bacterial activity. If your kitchen is cooler, you might want to try placing your starter in a slightly warmer spot, like near a radiator or in an oven with the light on (turned off, of course).\n\nAs for the flour, rye flour is a good choice for a sourdough starter because it contains a lot of nutrients that feed the yeast and bacteria. However, if you're having trouble with your starter, you might want to experiment with a different flour type. Whole wheat flour is another option, as it also has a high nutrient content and can help your starter to thrive. Just remember to adjust the feeding ratio accordingly, as whole wheat flour is denser than rye flour.\n\nI hope this helps! Keep an eye on your starter and give it a bit more time to wake up. With a little patience and the right conditions, you'll have a bubbly, active starter in no time",
